{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619997"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16601"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16601"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.17,0.02,0,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75972"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9292"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61473"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5322"},{"type":"tags","id":"10119"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22003"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75972"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOxytocin is a peptide hormone that plays crucial roles in human reproduction and lactation. It is synthesised in the hypothalamus and stored in the posterior pituitary gland.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the physiological actions of oxytocin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates uterine contractions and milk ejection","Promotes milk synthesis and cervical dilation","Stimulates follicle development and milk ejection","Promotes cervical dilation and suppresses lactation","Inhibits uterine contractions and promotes milk synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe two main physiological actions of oxytocin are \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulation of uterine contractions and milk ejection\u003C/strong\u003E. Its release is triggered by various stimuli including uterine distension during labour and nipple stimulation during breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring labour, oxytocin causes powerful contractions of uterine smooth muscle. During lactation, it causes contraction of myoepithelial cells in the mammary glands, leading to milk ejection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes milk synthesis and cervical dilation\u003C/strong\u003E - Milk synthesis is controlled by prolactin, not oxytocin. Cervical dilation involves multiple mechanisms including prostaglandins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates follicle development and milk ejection\u003C/strong\u003E - Follicular development is regulated by follicle-stimulating hormone, not oxytocin.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes cervical dilation and suppresses lactation\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxytocin does not suppress lactation; this is controlled by dopamine.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits uterine contractions and promotes milk synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxytocin stimulates rather than inhibits uterine contractions, and milk synthesis is controlled by prolactin.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Oxytocin stimulates uterine smooth muscle contraction during labour and delivery.","Oxytocin promotes milk ejection from the mammary glands during lactation.","Oxytocin is synthesised in the hypothalamus and stored in the posterior pituitary gland."],"references":["McGuire TM. Drugs affecting milk supply during lactation. Aust Prescr. 2018;41(1):7-9. Available from: https://www.nps.org.au/assets/11c542213d235076-e96a2c2ccd94-Drugs-affecting-milk-supply-during-lactation.pdf","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61473"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16601"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61473"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T19:11:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T19:13:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9292"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75972"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici